The Bowl

  • Bowl has 2,400 well-mixed red and white balls
  • What proportion are red?
  • We could take census–count all the balls
    • Long, boring
    • Doesn’t teach sampling

Take Virtual Sample of 50 Balls

  • We will take a random sample of 50 balls
    • Count the number of red balls
    • Divide by 50

Taking a Virtual Sample in Virtual 2020

  • function infer::rep_sample_n()
    • Take random samples of certain size from a data frame
      • tbl: name of data frame/tibble
      • size: number of cases in sample
      • reps: number of samples/replicates
      • replace =: whether to sample with or without replacement

set.seed(42)
s1 <- rep_sample_n(bowl, size = 50, reps = 1)
head(s1, 10)

How Much Variance in Each of These Results?

sample sample_size samples mean_prop standard_dev
Student Sample 50 20 0.371000 0.0741194
1,000 Samples 50 1000 0.372580 0.0673103
Samples with 100 100 1000 0.371150 0.0478693
Samples with 500 500 1000 0.374938 0.0184252

What This Is About

  • Sampling variation
  • Every sample drawn from a population is different
  • Larger the sample and/or larger the number of trials
    • You get closer to the true population mean
    • Standard deviation (i.e., variance) reduces
  • In this example, standard deviation declines
    • Student sample (50/20) = 0.0796 (1,000 observations)
    • 1,000 samples (50/1,000) = 0.0693 (50,000 obs.)
    • Samples with 500 (500/1,000) = 0.0194 (500,000 obs. )
  • Law of Large Numbers

Implication for Inference

  • If sampling of balls random, what we take out is an unbiased representation of the population
  • \(\therefore\), any result based on the sample can be generalized to the population
  • \(\therefore\), a sample statistic is a good guess of unknown population parameter
  • \(\therefore\), we don’t need to perform a census: can infer population value from sample

Definition of Inference

theory, methods, and practice of forming judgments about the parameters of a population and the reliability of statistical relationships, typically on the basis of random sampling

  • From ModernDive

Bootstrap Sampling

Bootstrap Sampling

  • What happens when you only have a single sample to work with?
  • How can you study effects of sampling variation?
  • Basic idea: resampling the sample with replacement
  • Resampling mimics the sampling variation across variety of samples
    • Approximates sampling distribution of the mean/proportion as in first example
  • To do bootstrap resampling,
    • Add argument to rep_sample_n(): replace = TRUE
  • Analog to biological amplification techniques

Basic Process of Bootstrap Resampling

  • Draw a sample of n balls from the bowl
    • Put them in a separate bowl
  • Resample
    • Take 1 ball out of the new bowl
    • Record its color
    • Return it to the new bowl (“with replacement”)
    • Repeat previous 3 steps until you have complete resample
  • Repeat process for all resamples you want to take
  • You may draw the same ball more than once
  • Some balls will never be drawn in a given resample
  • Each resample is different

Data for Bootstrap – Systolic Blood Pressure in Altibaixo, SP

  • City of Altibaixo, SP
    • Pop 64,347
  • Blood pressure file: altibaixo_sbp.rds
  • Only have funds to sample 200 Altibaixianos
alti_baix <- readRDS(here("altibaixo_sbp.rds"))
set.seed(42)
sbp_samp <- alti_baix %>% 
  rep_sample_n(size = 200, replace = FALSE) 
sbp_samp$replicate <- NULL

Making Bootstrap Resamples

  • Colored balls: Went back to the jar and took brand new samples
  • With the bp’s, can’t do that
  • Take our sample and resample from it
  • From sample of 200, we will take new sample of 200 with replacement
  • We will take 50 of these new resamples
resamples <- sbp_samp %>% 
  rep_sample_n(size = 200, replace = TRUE, reps = 50)

Find the Mean SBP of Each Resample

resample_means <- resamples %>%

Confidence Intervals

Confidence Intervals and Hypothesis Tests

  • Hypothesis tests: Trying to ascertain if a point estimate is accurate
    • Test statistic reflects the population parameter
  • Confidence Interval: what are some reasonable values of test statistic to consider when thinking about where the population parameter lies

Confidence Interval Meme

Determine Confidence Intervals – 2 Methods

  • Standard Error/Margin of Error
    • We looked at this
    • Will look at it again
  • Percentile method (for a 95% Confidence Interval)
    • Use the middle 95% of values of bootstrap distribution
    • Remember: Confidence Intervals determine values based on samples
    • Leave out 2.5% at both ends of the distribution
    • 2.5th and 97.5th percentiles: what is between them potentially contains population mean

infer Package Confidence Interval Workflow

specify() – Choose Variables

  • Just a response variable (variable of interest): argument response =
  • If also independent (explanatory) variables
    • Formula format: response ~ explanatory
      • Similar to regression
      • sbp_samp: sbp ~ NULL (no explanatory variable)
    • Arguments: response = and explanatory =
  • Similar to dplyr::group_by()

Example

sbp_samp %>%  # original sample used for bootstrap resampling

Expand to a 2 Variable Problem

  • Study to find if male bank employees were promoted at a higher rate than females
promotions <- moderndive::promotions
summarytools::ctable(promotions$decision, promotions$gender, prop = "c")

##   promoted            21 ( 87.5%)   14 ( 58.3%)   35 ( 72.9%)
##      Total            24 (100.0%)   24 (100.0%)   48 (100.0%)
## ---------- -------- ------------- ------------- -------------

Null Hypothesis

  • \(H_0\): proportion of men promoted equals proportion of women promoted
    • \(H_0: p_m - p_f=0\)
  • Add this to the workflow with the hypothesize() function
    • hypothesize(null = "independence")
  • “Independence”: response variable is independent of the explanatory variable

Set up infer Workflow

prom_shuffled <- promotions %>% 
  specify(formula = decision ~ gender, success = "promoted") %>% 
  hypothesize(null = "independence") %>% 
  generate(reps = 1000, type = "permute")
  • permute: alternative to bootstrap
  • Each input value (gender) gets randomly associated with a new output value (decision) for each replicate
  • This is equivalent to testing the data against the null hypothesis

Calculate the Test Statistic

null_dist <- promotions %>% 
  specify(formula = decision ~ gender, success = "promoted") %>% 
  hypothesize(null = "independence") %>% 
  generate(reps = 1000, type = "permute") %>% 
  calculate(stat = "diff in props", order = c("male", "female"))

## # A tibble: 1,000 x 2
##    replicate    stat
##        <int>   <dbl>
##  1         1 -0.125 
##  2         2  0.0417
##  3         3 -0.0417
##  4         4 -0.292 
##  5         5 -0.125 
##  6         6 -0.0417
##  7         7  0.0417
##  8         8 -0.208 
##  9         9  0.125 
## 10        10 -0.0417
## # ... with 990 more rows

Visualize the Replicates

What is True Proportion of Excess Males over Females

  • 2 methods of calculating
  • Traditional
    • 21 of 24 males promoted (0.875 of males)
    • 14 of 24 females promoted (0.583 of females)
    • Difference in promotion rate
      • (0.875 - 0.583) = 0.292
  • Is 0.292 a reasonable value given the data we have?

Using infer Workflow

  • Same workflow without hypothesize() and generate() steps
obs_diff <- promotions %>% 
  specify(decision ~ gender, success = "promoted") %>% 
  calculate(stat = "diff in props", order = c("male", "female"))
obs_diff
## # A tibble: 1 x 1
##    stat
##   <dbl>
## 1 0.292

Histogram with Real Value Added

Conclusion for the Promotions Question with CI

  • Failure to fall within shaded area suggests that equality (null hypothesis) is not the case
  • Can conclude that some discriminatory process is at work

Promotions Question as a Hypothesis Test

  • We have already postulated \(H_0\) and test statistic (\(p_m-p_f\))
  • We can calculate p-value with get_p_value()
null_dist %>% 
  get_p_value(obs_stat = obs_diff, direction = "right")
## # A tibble: 1 x 1
##   p_value
##     <dbl>
## 1   0.027
  • p-value is less than \(\alpha=0.05\); Reject \(H_0\)

What This Looks Like

Comparison with Traditional \(\chi^2\) Test

chisq_test(promotions, decision ~ gender)

Regression, Classification, Machine Learning & Modeling

Mixup in the Use of the Terms

  • Regression is at the same time
    • The principal statistical model of all
    • The principal machine learning tool of all

Uses of Modeling – Explanation

  • Describe and quantify relationships
    • Between outcome variable \(y\) and set of explanatory variables \(x\)
    • Summarize relationships
    • Identify causal relationships
    • Meeting assumptions important

Uses of Modeling – Prediction

  • Predict new values for an outcome variable \(y\) based on information in predictor variables \(x\)
    • Niceties of relations and assumptions not so important
    • Prediction accuracy defines a successful model
    • Especially on data not used to train the model

Machine Learning x Statistics

  • Explanatory models – Statistics
  • Prediction models – Machine Learning

Two Flavors of Machine Learning

  • Supervised – outcome variable exists and predictor variables used to determine changes in outcome variable
  • Unsupervised – no outcome variable; look for structure of predictor variables within cases

Basic Regression Model

  • Also called “parallel slopes” model
  • Forces two slopes to be parallel
    • assigns only 1 slope to age
fit_base <- lm(score ~ age + gender, data = tx_evals)
get_regression_table(fit_base)
## # A tibble: 3 x 7
##   term       estimate std_error statistic p_value lower_ci upper_ci
##   <chr>         <dbl>     <dbl>     <dbl>   <dbl>    <dbl>    <dbl>
## 1 intercept     4.48      0.125     35.8    0        4.24     4.73 
## 2 age          -0.009     0.003     -3.28   0.001   -0.014   -0.003
## 3 gendermale    0.191     0.052      3.63   0        0.087    0.294

Interpretation of Basic Model

  • Intercept for women (base category) is 4.484
  • Intercept for men is intercept + gendermale = 4.484 + 0.191 = 4.675
    • gendermale is an offset from the women’s score level
  • Slope for both females and males is -0.009
    • Everyone loses 0.009 from their score for every year they age
      • Ageism: For shame!

An Interaction Regression Model

  • Assumes values of age and gender depend on each other
  • Therefore men and women can have different slopes for age
  • Seen in different slopes in graph
  • Instead of +, use a * to show an interaction model
  • Regression lines in graph reflect interactions
    • Different slopes

Interaction Regression Table

fit_int <- lm(score ~ age * gender, data = tx_evals)
get_regression_table(fit_int)
## # A tibble: 4 x 7
##   term           estimate std_error statistic p_value lower_ci upper_ci
##   <chr>             <dbl>     <dbl>     <dbl>   <dbl>    <dbl>    <dbl>
## 1 intercept         4.88      0.205     23.8    0        4.48     5.29 
## 2 age              -0.018     0.004     -3.92   0       -0.026   -0.009
## 3 gendermale       -0.446     0.265     -1.68   0.094   -0.968    0.076
## 4 age:gendermale    0.014     0.006      2.45   0.015    0.003    0.024

Interpretation of Model – Females

  • Base category for categorical variable gender is female
  • Intercept: only for females Base score is 4.883
  • Slope (estimate for age): Again, only for females
    • For each year older, women lose 0.018 score

Model Again

get_regression_table(fit_int)
## # A tibble: 4 x 7
##   term           estimate std_error statistic p_value lower_ci upper_ci

## 4 age:gendermale    0.014     0.006      2.45   0.015    0.003    0.024

Interpretation of Model – Males

  • Estimate for gendermale (-0.446) is offset of intercept relative to female profs
  • Intercept for male instructors = 4.883 - 0.446 = 4.437
  • age:gendermale term is again offset of slope of women
  • Slope for males = -0.018 + 0.014 = -0.004

A Larger Regression Model

Data – Credit Model from ISLR

  • James, Witten, Hastie & Tibshirani, Introduction to Statistical Learning with Applications in R, 2017.
  • Measures the debt someone should be carrying based on predictor variables
    • Credit Limit
    • Income
    • Age
    • Credit Rating
  • All variables numeric

Scatter Plots of debt with income and credit rating

Fit a Model

  • With all numeric variables we can fit a basic model
fit_debt <- lm(debt ~ credit_limit + income + age, data = credit)
get_regression_table(fit_debt)
## # A tibble: 4 x 7
##   term         estimate std_error statistic p_value lower_ci upper_ci
##   <chr>           <dbl>     <dbl>     <dbl>   <dbl>    <dbl>    <dbl>
## 1 intercept    -342.       32.6      -10.5    0     -406.    -278.   
## 2 credit_limit    0.264     0.006     44.9    0        0.252    0.275
## 3 income         -7.56      0.389    -19.4    0       -8.33    -6.80 
## 4 age            -0.802     0.488     -1.64   0.101   -1.76     0.157

Interpretation of Model

  • Intercept is -$342.20
    • Credit card debt of someone with 0 credit limit, 0 income and 0 age
  • Credit limit value is $0.264: for every increase of $1 in credit limit, debt increases $0.26
  • Income value is -$7.563: for every $1 increase in income, people pay off $7.56 in debt
  • Age value is -0.802: for every year that people age, they pay off $0.80 in debt
